      "question": "If $x$ is a non-zero rational number and $y$ is an irrational number, then the nature of the product $xy$ is:",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Assume $x = \\frac{p}{q}$ where $p, q$ are integers, $q \\neq 0$, and $p \\neq 0$.",
          "Assume $xy = z$, where $z$ is a rational number.",
          "Then $y = \\frac{z}{x} = \\frac{z}{p/q} = \\frac{zq}{p}$.",
          "Since $z$ is rational and $x$ is a non-zero rational, the ratio of two rational numbers is always rational.",
          "This implies $y$ is rational, which contradicts the given fact that $y$ is irrational.",
          "Therefore, the product $xy$ must be irrational."
        ],
        "derivation": "$x \\in \\mathbb{Q}, x \\neq 0, y \\notin \\mathbb{Q} \\\\ \\text{Assume } xy = r, r \\in \\mathbb{Q} \\\\ y = \\frac{r}{x} \\\\ \\text{Since } r, x \\in \\mathbb{Q} \\text{ and } x \\neq 0, \\frac{r}{x} \\in \\mathbb{Q} \\\\ \\Rightarrow y \\in \\mathbb{Q} \\text{ (Contradiction)} \\\\ \\therefore xy \\notin \\mathbb{Q}$"
      },
